## 2. SEARCH INTENT & TARGET AUDIENCE

**Who is searching:** Primarily first-time renters aged 18–30 (young adults leaving home, college graduates entering the workforce), and secondarily repeat renters re-entering the market after several years (divorcees, people relocating for work, homeowners returning to renting). A smaller but significant cohort consists of international renters unfamiliar with U.S. rental norms.

**Buyer journey stage:** Early-to-mid informational. The searcher has decided to rent but has not yet begun actively searching for units. They need a complete process map before taking action.

**Problem being solved:** The user does not know what to do *in what order*—they may understand individual concepts (credit check, security deposit) but cannot sequence them into a coherent process. They are also trying to avoid costly mistakes (rejected applications, losing a security deposit, signing a bad lease).

**Expected answer format:** A numbered, sequential step-by-step guide with actionable checklists is the dominant format across all top-ranking competitors and both AI engines. Users also expect embedded explanatory detail (not just steps), FAQs for edge cases, and concrete numbers (dollar amounts, timelines, credit score thresholds).

